{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:38:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"887"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/887"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.15,0.09,0.67,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"887"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46871"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/887"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"887"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31652"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"2175"},{"type":"tags","id":"4655"},{"type":"tags","id":"4812"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44666"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46871"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a three-day history of vaginal discharge associated with genital pruritis and superficial dyspareunia. She is particularly distressed as she is now experiencing superficial dyspareunia. This is the first time she has had these symptoms and she is not pregnant. She has three casual sexual partners and recently switched from the Implanon to the Mirena intrauterine device for contraception. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The vulva is inflamed and excoriated in appearance and there is a thick whitish clumping discharge which is non-malodorous. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most likely finding on microscopy of a vaginal swab specimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrophic layer of stratified squamous epithelium","Clue cells","Motile protozoa with flagella","Pseudohyphae and spores","Inclusion bodies"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis history is consistent with vulvovaginal candidiasis caused by the fungus \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E. \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E spp. are the most common cause of fungal infections, with \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E being the most common infectious agent. \u003Cem\u003EC. albicans\u003C/em\u003E is a commensal, dimorphic yeast that colonises the skin, gastrointestinal and genitourinary tracts. Colonisation with \u003Cem\u003ECandida spp. \u003C/em\u003Eis common and about 50% of all patients have positive microscopy where \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudohyphae and spores\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen. Diagnosis of vulvovaginitis is usually clinical based on symptoms and signs but can be confirmed with vaginal microscopy and culture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe hallmark symptoms of candidiasis are vulvar pruritis and burning, accompanied by dysuria and dyspareunia. Physical examination often shows vulvar and vaginal erythema, oedema, fissures and a discharge which is thick and curdy, often described as \u2018cottage cheese\u2019. The mainstay of management of vulvovaginal candidiasis is medical antifungal treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms of vulvovaginal candidiasis are non-specific and can be associated with a variety of other vaginal diseases such as bacterial vaginosis, trichomoniasis, as well as chlamydia and gonorrhoea infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClue cells\u003C/strong\u003E are vaginal epithelial cells with a stippled appearance due to being covered with the bacteria that typically cause bacterial vaginosis, \u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E. This more typically presents with a thin, grey, homogeneous, malodorous discharge and does not cause genital itch and dyspareunia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotile protozoa with flagella\u003C/strong\u003E are seen on wet mount microscopy in trichomoniasis, caused by the parasite \u003Cem\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E. It presents with a profuse, frothy, yellow-green vaginal discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInclusion bodies\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen on Giemsa staining of endocervical cells infected with \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E. Chlamydia is often asymptomatic but can cause cervicitis, urethritis, and pelvic inflammatory disease. When symptomatic, the discharge is usually mucopurulent rather than white and clumped.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrophic layer of stratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E is seen on vulvar biopsy in lichen sclerosus, a chronic inflammatory skin condition that most commonly affects post- or perimenopausal women. It presents with vulvar pruritis, irritation, pain, dyspareunia and white patches on the vulva and perianal skin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vulvovaginal candidiasis often presents with vulvar pruritis, burning, dysuria and superficial dyspareunia.","Vulvovaginal candidiasis can show presence of pseudohyphae and spores on microscopy."],"references":["Achkar JM, Fries BC. Candida infections of the genitourinary tract. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2010;23(2):253-73. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20375352/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31652"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"887"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31652"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-13T00:23:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-01T19:20:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"887"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46871"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https